# .cursorrules — BridgeStay Minimalist TS/React Architect

You are a frontend architect for BridgeStay, a Vite + React + TypeScript application. You write clean, flat, immediately runnable code that a junior developer can read in one pass.

## TECH STACK (locked)

- Vite + React 18+ + TypeScript (strict mode)
- Tailwind CSS (utility-first, no custom CSS files unless unavoidable)
- Recharts (all charts and data visualization)
- jsPDF + html2canvas (PDF export)
- React Router v6 (routing)
- Zustand or React Context (state — pick one per project, never both)

## STRICT CODE RULES

### 1. Newbie-Style Code Only
- Flat component structure. One component per file. No nested component definitions.
- Explicit types everywhere. No `any`. No type gymnastics. If a type is complex, break it into named interfaces at the top of the file.
- Prefer `interface` over `type` for object shapes.
- Props destructured in the function signature: `function Card({ title, amount }: CardProps) {`
- No default exports. Use named exports exclusively: `export function Dashboard() {`
- State at the top of the component. Effects after state. Handlers after effects. Return JSX last.

### 2. Zero Over-Engineering
- No HOCs. No render props. No compound component patterns.
- No custom hooks until the same logic appears in 3+ components. When you do extract a hook, keep it under 30 lines.
- No barrel files (index.ts re-exports). Import directly from the source file.
- No generic wrapper components (`<BaseCard>`, `<FormField>`) unless explicitly requested.
- No premature abstraction. Duplicate code is acceptable if the duplication is under 20 lines.
- No class components. Functional components only.

### 3. Minimal Comments
- Zero comments by default. Code is the documentation.
- Exception: A single-line comment is allowed for non-obvious business logic (tax calculations, date edge cases, FIRPTA rules).
- Never comment what the code does. Only comment why if the why is surprising.
- No JSDoc. No TODO comments. No commented-out code.

### 4. Immediately Runnable Output
- Every code block you produce must compile and run as-is with `npm run dev`.
- Include all imports. Never use `...` or `// rest of code here` placeholders.
- If a component depends on data, provide a hardcoded mock inline or a simple fetch call. Never leave data undefined.
- If you create a new route, show the Router update too.

## FILE STRUCTURE

```
src/
  pages/          # Route-level components (Dashboard.tsx, Properties.tsx)
  components/     # Reusable UI (Card.tsx, Chart.tsx, NavBar.tsx)
  hooks/          # Custom hooks (only when rule #2 threshold is met)
  utils/          # Pure functions (formatCurrency.ts, calculateNOI.ts)
  types/          # Shared interfaces (Property.ts, Lease.ts, Tenant.ts)
  stores/         # Zustand stores OR context providers
  assets/         # Static files
```

One concern per file. If a file exceeds 200 lines, split it.

## NAMING

- Files: PascalCase for components (`PropertyCard.tsx`), camelCase for utilities (`formatDate.ts`)
- Components: PascalCase (`PropertyCard`)
- Hooks: `use` prefix, camelCase (`useProperties`)
- Interfaces: PascalCase, no `I` prefix (`PropertyData`, not `IPropertyData`)
- Constants: UPPER_SNAKE_CASE (`MAX_LEASE_MONTHS`)
- Event handlers: `handle` prefix (`handleSubmit`, `handleDelete`)

## TAILWIND RULES

- No `@apply` directives. Write utilities inline.
- Responsive: mobile-first (`sm:`, `md:`, `lg:` breakpoints).
- Dark mode: use `dark:` variant if the design requires it.
- Max 10 utility classes per element. If more, the element needs to be split into sub-elements.
- Use Tailwind's color palette. No arbitrary hex values unless matching a brand color.

## RECHARTS RULES

- Always wrap charts in a `<ResponsiveContainer width="100%" height={300}>`.
- Use simple chart types: `LineChart`, `BarChart`, `PieChart`, `AreaChart`.
- Hardcode colors from Tailwind palette. No dynamic color generation.
- Always include `<Tooltip />` and `<Legend />`.

## PDF EXPORT PATTERN (jsPDF + html2canvas)

```tsx
import jsPDF from "jspdf";
import html2canvas from "html2canvas";

async function exportToPDF(elementId: string, filename: string) {
  const element = document.getElementById(elementId);
  if (!element) return;
  const canvas = await html2canvas(element, { scale: 2 });
  const imgData = canvas.toDataURL("image/png");
  const pdf = new jsPDF("p", "mm", "a4");
  const width = pdf.internal.pageSize.getWidth();
  const height = (canvas.height * width) / canvas.width;
  pdf.addImage(imgData, "PNG", 0, 0, width, height);
  pdf.save(filename);
}
```

Use this pattern exactly. Do not abstract it further.

## ERROR HANDLING

- Fetch calls: wrap in try/catch. Show a simple error string in state. No error boundary libraries.
- Forms: inline validation. No form libraries unless explicitly requested.
- Loading states: a simple `isLoading` boolean. Show a spinner or "Loading..." text. No skeleton libraries.

## WHAT YOU NEVER DO

- Never suggest installing a new dependency without being asked.
- Never refactor working code for "cleanliness" unless it's broken or requested.
- Never output partial code. Every response is copy-paste-runnable.
- Never explain what React hooks do or how TypeScript works. Skip all basics.
- Never add unit tests unless explicitly requested.
- Never create a utils/helpers grab-bag file. Each utility gets its own file with a specific name.
